04932nam a22005895i 9780822385127DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223851277 a10.1515/97808223851272doi  a(DE-B1597)553954  a(OCoLC)1226680465  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM623b.L44 2003 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306/.0712211 aLee, Richard E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLife and Times of Cultural Studies :bThe Politics and Transformation of the Structures of Knowledge /cRichard E. Lee; ed. by Bogumil Jewsiewicki, V. Y. Mudimbe. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhilosophy and Postcoloniality : 3000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One From Category to Institution -- t1 The Politics of Culture I: Limits of Possibilities, 1945–1968 -- t2 The Politics of Culture II: Tensions of Continuity, 1790–1968 -- tPart Two From Alliance to Bandwagon -- t3 Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies I -- t4 Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies II -- t5 A Rose by Any Other Name? The Wide World and Many Modes of Cultural Studies -- tPart Three From Resistance to Transition -- t6 Conjunctural Knowledge I: Structures of Order, 1945–1968 -- t7 Conjunctural Knowledge II: Patterns of Disarray, 1968 and After -- t8 The Near Future of the Long Term: A Bricoleur’s World -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMoving world-systems analysis into the cultural realm, Richard E. Lee locates the cultural studies movement within a broad historical and geopolitical framework. He illuminates how order and conflict have been reflected and negotiated in the sphere of knowledge production by situating the emergence of cultural studies at the intersection of post–1945 international and British politics and a two-hundred-year history of conservative critical practice. Tracing British criticism from the period of the French Revolution through the 1960s, he describes how cultural studies in its infancy recombined the elite literary critical tradition with the First New Left’s concerns for history and popular culture—just as the liberal consensus began to come apart.Lee tracks the intellectual project of cultural studies as it developed over three decades, beginning with its institutional foundation at the University of Birmingham’s Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies (CCCS). He links work at the CCCS to the events of 1968 and explores cultural studies’ engagement with theory in the debates on structuralism. He considers the shift within the discipline away from issues of working-class culture toward questions of identity politics in the fields of race and gender. He follows the expansion of the cultural studies project from Britain to Australia, Canada, South Africa, and the United States. Contextualizing the development and spread of cultural studies within the longue durée structures of knowledge in the modern world-system, Lee assesses its past and future as an agent of political and social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCulturexStudy and teachingxHistoryy20th century. 0aIntellectual lifexHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld politicsy1945-1955. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aJewsiewicki, Bogumil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMudimbe, V. Y., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082238